# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: Other | Scene: AThreatIsUttered
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "The winter's grace festival was under way, and all throughout Rosanna, people had begun to decorate their homes."
    new "The winter's grace festival was under way, and all throughout Rosanna, people had begun to decorate their homes."

    old "Castle Reinmeer was no exception, covered from floor to ceiling in extravagent gold and silver garlands."
    new "Castle Reinmeer was no exception, covered from floor to ceiling in extravagent gold and silver garlands."

    old "Standing near the entrance to the great hall, Sarah greeted everyone who visited."
    new "Standing near the entrance to the great hall, Sarah greeted everyone who visited."

    old "Inside the great hall, Thomas sat atop his throne in full regalia."
    new "Inside the great hall, Thomas sat atop his throne in full regalia."

    old "Sarah could see him slouched, waving disinterested at the crowd. And yet, even her brother seemed kingly when dressed up like this."
    new "Sarah could see him slouched, waving disinterested at the crowd. And yet, even her brother seemed kingly when dressed up like this."

    old "Noble wife\" \"Aah, Princess, thank you for allowing us to attend, the castle looks incredible!"
    new "Noble wife\" \"Aah, Princess, thank you for allowing us to attend, the castle looks incredible!"

    old "Sarah smiled and nodded."
    new "Sarah smiled and nodded."

    old "We're happy to host you."
    new "We're happy to host you."

    old "Smiles, compliments, condolences for her father, it was all an endless repetition, but Sarah shouldered it and never showed her exhaustion."
    new "Smiles, compliments, condolences for her father, it was all an endless repetition, but Sarah shouldered it and never showed her exhaustion."

    old "As the room filled up, Sarah could hear the buzz from inside grow louder."
    new "As the room filled up, Sarah could hear the buzz from inside grow louder."

    old "There was the occasional hoot and cheer from the crowd as performers juggled or somersaulted through the aisles. Some performers managed both at the same time."
    new "There was the occasional hoot and cheer from the crowd as performers juggled or somersaulted through the aisles. Some performers managed both at the same time."

    old "With most of the nobles now in attendance, Sarah signalled the servants to continue welcoming any stragglers, as she went inside."
    new "With most of the nobles now in attendance, Sarah signalled the servants to continue welcoming any stragglers, as she went inside."

    old "As soon as she stepped into the great hall, she felt the heat press upon her skin."
    new "As soon as she stepped into the great hall, she felt the heat press upon her skin."

    old "The long tables were covered from end to end with different dishes. The many smells combining in the air, filling the great hall with a rare scent of festivity."
    new "The long tables were covered from end to end with different dishes. The many smells combining in the air, filling the great hall with a rare scent of festivity."

    old "Sarah continued walking through the center of the hall, up to the dais to take her place next to Thomas."
    new "Sarah continued walking through the center of the hall, up to the dais to take her place next to Thomas."

    old "She waved politely at faces she couldn't remember, and a few she could. Varga was there, as was Marion."
    new "She waved politely at faces she couldn't remember, and a few she could. Varga was there, as was Marion."

    old "Sarah wished she had the time to speak to them."
    new "Sarah wished she had the time to speak to them."

    old "Climing up the stairs, she sat down in a smaller, lower seat, besides Thomas. It was close enough to speak, but so far away from anyone else, she doubted they could hear them."
    new "Climing up the stairs, she sat down in a smaller, lower seat, besides Thomas. It was close enough to speak, but so far away from anyone else, she doubted they could hear them."

    old "Everyone here?"
    new "Everyone here?"

    old "Sarah waved her hand as if to dismiss the question."
    new "Sarah waved her hand as if to dismiss the question."

    old "Anyone who isn't here yet is probably not important enough to wait on."
    new "Anyone who isn't here yet is probably not important enough to wait on."

    old "Alright, shall I begin then?"
    new "Alright, shall I begin then?"

    old "She wondered why she felt so distant today. She always loved the winter grace festival."
    new "She wondered why she felt so distant today. She always loved the winter grace festival."

    old "Perhaps, she thought, it's because this was the first major festival without her father. The day felt tainted, somehow."
    new "Perhaps, she thought, it's because this was the first major festival without her father. The day felt tainted, somehow."

    old "Thomas rose up from his seat, and an attendant stomped hard on the floor three times, bringing the room to a silence."
    new "Thomas rose up from his seat, and an attendant stomped hard on the floor three times, bringing the room to a silence."

    old "Let me begin by welcoming all of you to this year's winter grace festival."
    new "Let me begin by welcoming all of you to this year's winter grace festival."

    old "I stand here, happy to see so many friendly faces, and to see this great hall sing with a joy that can only come from good friends and good food."
    new "I stand here, happy to see so many friendly faces, and to see this great hall sing with a joy that can only come from good friends and good food."

    old "But there is also a pain in my heart. An absence that I feel, as surely as all of you."
    new "But there is also a pain in my heart. An absence that I feel, as surely as all of you."

    old "My father presided over countless of these gatherings, but for me, this is a first."
    new "My father presided over countless of these gatherings, but for me, this is a first."

    old "Even now, I find myself instinctively looking at the door, waiting for him to walk through. A winter festival without him, almost seems, wrong."
    new "Even now, I find myself instinctively looking at the door, waiting for him to walk through. A winter festival without him, almost seems, wrong."

    old "Sarah found herself surprised to see her brother echo her own feelings so closely."
    new "Sarah found herself surprised to see her brother echo her own feelings so closely."

    old "The winter grace festival is about togetherness, so how do we celebrate that, when we are still mourning a loss that has separated us?"
    new "The winter grace festival is about togetherness, so how do we celebrate that, when we are still mourning a loss that has separated us?"

    old "We used to celebrate it with my father, but I propose, that this year, we instead celebrate in honour of him."
    new "We used to celebrate it with my father, but I propose, that this year, we instead celebrate in honour of him."

    old "Those of you who had the privilege of truly knowing my father, knew how much he enjoyed the winter grace festival."
    new "Those of you who had the privilege of truly knowing my father, knew how much he enjoyed the winter grace festival."

    old "The company, the decorations, the food...the beer."
    new "The company, the decorations, the food...the beer."

    old "A roaring laugh erupted from the room."
    new "A roaring laugh erupted from the room."

    old "So let us honour my father, by keeping his memory alive and celebrating this year's winter grace festival in the way that he would have wanted us to."
    new "So let us honour my father, by keeping his memory alive and celebrating this year's winter grace festival in the way that he would have wanted us to."

    old "Thomas raised a chalice."
    new "Thomas raised a chalice."

    old "To my father, a king without equal."
    new "To my father, a king without equal."

    old "All across the hall, others raised their cups and yelled out their toasts."
    new "All across the hall, others raised their cups and yelled out their toasts."

    old "As Thomas fell back into his seat, the party truly took off."
    new "As Thomas fell back into his seat, the party truly took off."

    old "Thomas looked at Sarah, he seemed utterly wracked and exhausted."
    new "Thomas looked at Sarah, he seemed utterly wracked and exhausted."

    old "How did I do?"
    new "How did I do?"

    old "Sarah looked at Thomas, stunned."
    new "Sarah looked at Thomas, stunned."

    old "You were incredible, Thomas."
    new "You were incredible, Thomas."

    old "You think so? I spend all night writing and memorizing it."
    new "You think so? I spend all night writing and memorizing it."

    old "She watched as her brother slouched back into his seat. He had been somewhat of a true king for a moment, but Sarah slowly realized it didn't come easy to him."
    new "She watched as her brother slouched back into his seat. He had been somewhat of a true king for a moment, but Sarah slowly realized it didn't come easy to him."

    old "The night carried on, and Sarah and Thomas spend it eating, receiving gifts from the nobles and listening to their troubles."
    new "The night carried on, and Sarah and Thomas spend it eating, receiving gifts from the nobles and listening to their troubles."

    old "It was only towards the end of the night, when the mood suddenly shifted."
    new "It was only towards the end of the night, when the mood suddenly shifted."

    old "The door to the main hall burst open, each frame slamming into the walls. The sound echoed through the hall and a gust of wind was carried in."
    new "The door to the main hall burst open, each frame slamming into the walls. The sound echoed through the hall and a gust of wind was carried in."

    old "A dreadful silence came over the room as a everyone turned their heads to see the source of the disturbance."
    new "A dreadful silence came over the room as a everyone turned their heads to see the source of the disturbance."

    old "Marching through the center of the hall, in great strides, was a man."
    new "Marching through the center of the hall, in great strides, was a man."

    old "His skin was a soft oaken brown, darker than any other in the room by far. His dark hair was swept back, cut in a practical fashion. A military fashion."
    new "His skin was a soft oaken brown, darker than any other in the room by far. His dark hair was swept back, cut in a practical fashion. A military fashion."

    old "His young face was contrasted by his old eyes."
    new "His young face was contrasted by his old eyes."

    old "Just as his appearance and his style, the clothes he wore were foreign as well. A soft swirling white, mixed with a deep purple and the occasional leather patches of armor."
    new "Just as his appearance and his style, the clothes he wore were foreign as well. A soft swirling white, mixed with a deep purple and the occasional leather patches of armor."

    old "Sarah had never seen a man dressed like this, but she didn't need to in order to know that this man hailed from the eastern desert."
    new "Sarah had never seen a man dressed like this, but she didn't need to in order to know that this man hailed from the eastern desert."

    old "He was too alien to belong to her world."
    new "He was too alien to belong to her world."

    old "The man strode across the hall, ending up at the feet of the stairs that led up to the dais."
    new "The man strode across the hall, ending up at the feet of the stairs that led up to the dais."

    old "Off to the sides, the guards had drawn in closer, but Thomas had waved to hold them off, seemingly more intrigued than afraid."
    new "Off to the sides, the guards had drawn in closer, but Thomas had waved to hold them off, seemingly more intrigued than afraid."

    old "The foreign man fell to one knee."
    new "The foreign man fell to one knee."

    old "King Thomas, I humbly greet you."
    new "King Thomas, I humbly greet you."

    old "Thomas motioned for the man to stand up."
    new "Thomas motioned for the man to stand up."

    old "Please rise, visitor."
    new "Please rise, visitor."

    old "The man did as instructed. His eyes fell directly on Thomas, before switching towards Sarah."
    new "The man did as instructed. His eyes fell directly on Thomas, before switching towards Sarah."

    old "He only stared at her for a moment, before returning to Thomas, but to Sarah it felt like an eternity."
    new "He only stared at her for a moment, before returning to Thomas, but to Sarah it felt like an eternity."

    old "There was something in this man's eyes. A purpose. All the others in the castle looked at her for who she was, a princess, but this man had the eyes of a predator."
    new "There was something in this man's eyes. A purpose. All the others in the castle looked at her for who she was, a princess, but this man had the eyes of a predator."

    old "I have travelled far, hailing from deep within what you call the eastern desert, and I have come to deliver a gift, from my Master to you, king Thomas."
    new "I have travelled far, hailing from deep within what you call the eastern desert, and I have come to deliver a gift, from my Master to you, king Thomas."

    old "The man's accent was faint, he was clearly well educated to speak the language of Rosanna so effortlessly."
    new "The man's accent was faint, he was clearly well educated to speak the language of Rosanna so effortlessly."

    old "Thomas was now leaning in, wanting to know more."
    new "Thomas was now leaning in, wanting to know more."

    old "A gift?"
    new "A gift?"

    old "The emissary nodded."
    new "The emissary nodded."

    old "My master, the great Khan Hassar, has tasked me to bring you a gift of peace."
    new "My master, the great Khan Hassar, has tasked me to bring you a gift of peace."

    old "The room was still silent as a crypt."
    new "The room was still silent as a crypt."

    old "Khan Hassar bears a great burden, placed upon him by the stars in heaven. He is to bring unity to this world, and bind all peoples together into a single tribe."
    new "Khan Hassar bears a great burden, placed upon him by the stars in heaven. He is to bring unity to this world, and bind all peoples together into a single tribe."

    old "In service of this great task, he has brought together the tribes of the desert, and brought low the far-eastern nations from beyond the desert."
    new "In service of this great task, he has brought together the tribes of the desert, and brought low the far-eastern nations from beyond the desert."

    old "Great Emperors of dynasties that have endured for millenia, have bowed their heads low to Khan Hassar."
    new "Great Emperors of dynasties that have endured for millenia, have bowed their heads low to Khan Hassar."

    old "But others, sought to impede his great task. It is because of them that I must sadly bear an offer of peace in one hand, and a warning in the other."
    new "But others, sought to impede his great task. It is because of them that I must sadly bear an offer of peace in one hand, and a warning in the other."

    old "The emissary reached into a bag and pulled something out."
    new "The emissary reached into a bag and pulled something out."

    old "A woman shrieked loudly, breaking through the silence. The room began to grow rowdy. Men began to shout obscenities."
    new "A woman shrieked loudly, breaking through the silence. The room began to grow rowdy. Men began to shout obscenities."

    old "Sarah felt herself grow weak, but forced herself to look on. Look at the decapitated head that the emissary was now holding up for all to see."
    new "Sarah felt herself grow weak, but forced herself to look on. Look at the decapitated head that the emissary was now holding up for all to see."

    old "This king was proud. Too proud to bend his head for Khan Hassar, and for this, he lost it."
    new "This king was proud. Too proud to bend his head for Khan Hassar, and for this, he lost it."

    old "But, along with him, more than a hundred thousand of his countrymen perished with him, dying to defend this fool's honour."
    new "But, along with him, more than a hundred thousand of his countrymen perished with him, dying to defend this fool's honour."

    old "And despite his arrogance, his sons and daughters were still made slaves to the Tribe."
    new "And despite his arrogance, his sons and daughters were still made slaves to the Tribe."

    old "Khan Hassar wept for the senselessness of this carnage, and he vowed that before delivering war, he would always offer peace, so that this tragedy might never repeat itself."
    new "Khan Hassar wept for the senselessness of this carnage, and he vowed that before delivering war, he would always offer peace, so that this tragedy might never repeat itself."

    old "The emissary threw the head halfway up the stairs, where it remained, delicately balanced."
    new "The emissary threw the head halfway up the stairs, where it remained, delicately balanced."

    old "And so, I was sent here. Sent to deliver this great offer of peace."
    new "And so, I was sent here. Sent to deliver this great offer of peace."

    old "King Thomas, on behalf of Khan Hassar, I command you to prostrate yourself before me as if I were him."
    new "King Thomas, on behalf of Khan Hassar, I command you to prostrate yourself before me as if I were him."

    old "Do this, and Khan Hassar will spare you and the entire nation of Rosanna a bloodshed you cannot begin to imagine."
    new "Do this, and Khan Hassar will spare you and the entire nation of Rosanna a bloodshed you cannot begin to imagine."

    old "Open your gates, lay down your weapons and disband your armies, and the great horde will sweep through this nation without breaking so much as a blade of grass."
    new "Open your gates, lay down your weapons and disband your armies, and the great horde will sweep through this nation without breaking so much as a blade of grass."

    old "But reject this offer, and we will turn your nation to ashes. Bind your nation's sons and daughters into slavery. Run the great rivers red with blood."
    new "But reject this offer, and we will turn your nation to ashes. Bind your nation's sons and daughters into slavery. Run the great rivers red with blood."

    old "By now, the gathering of nobles was screaming and had begun throwing things at the emissary, so outraged were they at his demands."
    new "By now, the gathering of nobles was screaming and had begun throwing things at the emissary, so outraged were they at his demands."

    old "The Emissary remained perfectly still, unbothered with the screams of the crowd."
    new "The Emissary remained perfectly still, unbothered with the screams of the crowd."

    old "His iron gaze remained fixed on Thomas and Sarah."
    new "His iron gaze remained fixed on Thomas and Sarah."

    old "Sarah had listened intently, and felt like a fist was closing around her throat."
    new "Sarah had listened intently, and felt like a fist was closing around her throat."

    old "She looked at Thomas, who had turned white as marble."
    new "She looked at Thomas, who had turned white as marble."

    old "She understood that just as she looked to Thomas, many of the nobles now did too."
    new "She understood that just as she looked to Thomas, many of the nobles now did too."

    old "They had to be decisive."
    new "They had to be decisive."

    old "Sarah stood up and walked next to Thomas. She grabbed him by the shoulder and woke him from his stupor."
    new "Sarah stood up and walked next to Thomas. She grabbed him by the shoulder and woke him from his stupor."

    old "Looking down at him, she whispered her instruction."
    new "Looking down at him, she whispered her instruction."

    old "None may threaten Rosanna; make an example of him!"
    new "None may threaten Rosanna; make an example of him!"

    old "Thomas rose up from his throne."
    new "Thomas rose up from his throne."

    old "It is not up for barbarians from the desert to come to the land of civilized men and utter threats."
    new "It is not up for barbarians from the desert to come to the land of civilized men and utter threats."

    old "Perhaps, your lack of education is to be blamed. If so, allow me to educate you now."
    new "Perhaps, your lack of education is to be blamed. If so, allow me to educate you now."

    old "Thomas motioned for the guards to move forward. They seized the man, who offered up no struggle, even as they forced him to his knees."
    new "Thomas motioned for the guards to move forward. They seized the man, who offered up no struggle, even as they forced him to his knees."

    old "The crowd began to roar as if they had never seen a greater spectacle."
    new "The crowd began to roar as if they had never seen a greater spectacle."

    old "Guards! Bring me this creature's head!"
    new "Guards! Bring me this creature's head!"

    old "The largest of the guards began to unsheath his blade, a great two-handed weapon. He balanced the blade over the emissary's neck, then pulled it back, holding it overhead."
    new "The largest of the guards began to unsheath his blade, a great two-handed weapon. He balanced the blade over the emissary's neck, then pulled it back, holding it overhead."

    old "Sarah, closer than anyone else, noticed a single tear crawling down the emissary's cheek."
    new "Sarah, closer than anyone else, noticed a single tear crawling down the emissary's cheek."

    old "He looked up, staring directly at Sarah."
    new "He looked up, staring directly at Sarah."

    old "His mouth moved, but nobody could hear anything over the frenzied crowd."
    new "His mouth moved, but nobody could hear anything over the frenzied crowd."

    old "I weep for you, Sarah saw him mouthing."
    new "I weep for you, Sarah saw him mouthing."

    old "The guard swung the blade down as though it were a plow. The blade easily cut through the emissary's neck."
    new "The guard swung the blade down as though it were a plow. The blade easily cut through the emissary's neck."

    old "His head rolled forward, ending up at the feet of the stairs."
    new "His head rolled forward, ending up at the feet of the stairs."

    old "The guard walked over and handed the bloodied head over to Thomas."
    new "The guard walked over and handed the bloodied head over to Thomas."

    old "Grabbing the head by the hair near the scalp, Thomas raised it up over his head, the blood still leaking."
    new "Grabbing the head by the hair near the scalp, Thomas raised it up over his head, the blood still leaking."

    old "Sarah thought she would go deaf, so loudly did the nobles scream and cheer king Thomas."
    new "Sarah thought she would go deaf, so loudly did the nobles scream and cheer king Thomas."

    old "The festivities carried on deep into the night, as if the attendants were possessed by an otherwordly zeal."
    new "The festivities carried on deep into the night, as if the attendants were possessed by an otherwordly zeal."

    old "Send him back to the deserts he crawled out of."
    new "Send him back to the deserts he crawled out of."

    old "He rose up his hands to silence the crowd. Only when everyone was silent, did he speak."
    new "He rose up his hands to silence the crowd. Only when everyone was silent, did he speak."

    old "You have travelled far to utter your threats, but they do not frighten us."
    new "You have travelled far to utter your threats, but they do not frighten us."

    old "Go back to your master and tell him that Rosanna seeks peace with all, but we bend for none."
    new "Go back to your master and tell him that Rosanna seeks peace with all, but we bend for none."

    old "Should his barbarian horde come to our land, we will do as we have done for centuries, and drive you back into the desert where you belong."
    new "Should his barbarian horde come to our land, we will do as we have done for centuries, and drive you back into the desert where you belong."

    old "The emissary bowed low one last time."
    new "The emissary bowed low one last time."

    old "King Thomas, with great sadness, I receive your message and will carry it back to my Khan."
    new "King Thomas, with great sadness, I receive your message and will carry it back to my Khan."

    old "One day, very soon, you will come to regret this decision. For all my life, I will bear the guilt of not having been able to save you and your people from your own pride."
    new "One day, very soon, you will come to regret this decision. For all my life, I will bear the guilt of not having been able to save you and your people from your own pride."

    old "As the emissary left, the room fell silent again."
    new "As the emissary left, the room fell silent again."

    old "The people had solemnly begun to realize there would be war."
    new "The people had solemnly begun to realize there would be war."

    old "The festivities carried on for a short time after, but with the mood having soured, many soon began to take their leave."
    new "The festivities carried on for a short time after, but with the mood having soured, many soon began to take their leave."

    old "It wasn't long before the castle, once filled with sounds and warmth, grew silent and cold."
    new "It wasn't long before the castle, once filled with sounds and warmth, grew silent and cold."

